  "body": "TL;DR http://swarm-gateways.net/bzz:/swarm/ works but http://swarm-gateways.net/bzz:/swarm does not.\n\nThe issue with the trailing slash in swarm.\n\nProblem: The swarm landing page works when called like this\nhttp://52.169.106.34:32208/bzz:/49d31de7f834a2d8b9d7e4a8f365ba9b5df8b1215c4f13cae4a7179797155f2b/\nor this:\nhttp://swarm-gateways.net/bzz:/swarm/\n\nbut fails when called like this:\nhttp://52.169.106.34:32208/bzz:/49d31de7f834a2d8b9d7e4a8f365ba9b5df8b1215c4f13cae4a7179797155f2b\nor this:\nhttp://swarm-gateways.net/bzz:/swarm\n\nthe reason is that while the name 'swarm' or the hash \"49d31de7f834...\" return the same html content regardless of whether you include a trailing /, the realative paths within the html document are interptreted differently. In one case a realtive path ./tohere will reference a file subrdinate to 'swarm' -- that is bzz:/swarm/tohere -- whereas in the other case it will reference a (non-existing) file bzz:/tohere\n\nThe slash \"/\" is a special character for the browser even if it is deliberately not special in swarm.\n\nI see no easy way of fixing this issue because it seems to be based on an incompatibility between how browsers treat the / character and how they are handled in manifests.\n\nFollow up question: can I register the name \"swarm/\" too and what happens then when I call swarm-gateways.net/bzz:/swarm/\n",
